## {{ rule.title }}

[DBA-USA Art. 28](https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-trty/germany.pdf) (Limitation on Benefits, as amended by the 2006 Protocol) gates every other treaty benefit. A treaty resourcing claim under [Art. 23](https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-trty/germany.pdf) / [IRS Pub. 514](https://www.irs.gov/publications/p514) requires LOB qualification under one of:

- **Art. 28(2)(c)** — publicly traded company
- **Art. 28(2)(a) / (f)** — qualified resident (this is the typical posture for an individual U.S. citizen / long-term resident of Germany)
- **Art. 28(4)** — active business
- **Art. 28(5) / (7)** — derivative benefits
- **Art. 28(7)** — competent authority discretionary determination

If none applies (`lob_qualification_category=not_qualified`), treaty re-sourcing is disabled and the engine fails closed when the taxpayer also claims `use_treaty_resourcing=true`. When treaty benefits ARE claimed, [IRS Form 8833](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-8833) disclosure is required under 26 U.S.C. § 6114.

